ture_review.md:6:How robust are neural thicket-style ensembles (constructed from perturbations around pretrained weights) under adversarial attacks and OOD shifts, and what diversity mechanisms most improve resilience?\nliterature_review.md:23:- Paper-finder service (diligent mode)\nliterature_review.md:46:The literature converges on a common observation: ensembles improve both confidence calibration and robustness, but robustness gains vary strongly with **expert diversity** and **error independence**. Work from adversarial training emphasizes distributional coverage of attacks, while OOD work emphasizes score separation and uncertainty quality. Newer methods (including Neural Thickets/RandOpt) shift focus toward generating many nearby experts around pretrained models, making diversity generation more compute-efficient than full retraining.\nliterature_review.md:50:### 1) Neural Thickets: Diverse Task Experts Are Dense Around Pretrained Weights (2026)\nliterature_review.md:52:- **Source**: arXiv (2603.12228)\nliterature_review.md:55:- **Datasets Used**: Multi-task/post-training benchmarks (see repo scripts/data docs).\nliterature_review.md:57:- **Code Available**: Yes (`code/neural-thickets-randopt`).\nliterature_review.md:60:### 2) Robust Deep Learning Ensemble against Deception (2020)\nliterature_review.md:62:- **Source**: IEEE TDSC + arXiv (2009.06589)\nliterature_review.md:63:- **Key Contribution**: Joint defense against adversarial and OOD inputs via diversity-driven verification (XEnsemble).\nliterature_review.md:70:### 3) Ensemble Adversarial Training: Attacks and Defenses (2017)\nliterature_review.md:75:- **Datasets Used**: Image classification benchmarks (e.g., MNIST/ImageNet variants in original work).\nliterature_review.md:79:### 4) Simple and Scalable Predictive Uncertainty Estimation using Deep Ensembles (2016)\nliterature_review.md:88:### 5) Out-of-Distribution Detection Using an Ensemble of Self Supervised Leave-out Classifiers (2018)\nliterature_review.md:97:### 6) Enhancing Certifiable Robustness via a Deep Model Ensemble (2019)\nliterature_review.md:105:### 7) Certifying Joint Adversarial Robustness for Model Ensembles (2020)\nliterature_review.md:113:### 8) PEP: Parameter Ensembling by Perturbation (2020)\nliterature_review.md:121:### 9) Sequential Bayesian Neural Subnetwork Ensembles (2022)\nliterature_review.md:128:### 10) Batch-Ensemble Stochastic Neural Networks for OOD Detection (2022)\nliterature_review.md:134:### 11) On the Usefulness of Deep Ensemble Diversity for OOD Detection (2022)\nliterature_review.md:139:- **Code Available**: Yes (`code/ens-div-ood-detect`).\nliterature_review.md:142:### 12) Hierarchical Pruning of Deep Ensembles with Focal Diversity (2023)\nliterature_review.md:152:- **Perturbation-based ensembling**: experts sampled via parameter perturbations around pretrained weights (PEP, Neural Thickets).\nliterature_review.md:159:- Single pretrained model (no ensemble).\nliterature_review.md:162:- Parameter-sharing ensemble variants (BatchEnsemble-style).\nliterature_review.md:169:- **OOD detection**: AUROC, AUPR, FPR95 (and optionally detection error).\nliterature_review.md:175:- CIFAR-10 / CIFAR-100 (core ID benchmarks).\nliterature_review.md:176:- SVHN, TinyImageNet, LSUN, iSUN, Textures, OpenImage-O (common OOD sets).\nliterature_review.md:184:4. Cost-aware scaling laws (experts vs robustness gain) remain undercharacterized.\nliterature_review.md:189:  - ID: CIFAR-10 (downloaded).\nliterature_review.md:190:  - OOD: SVHN (downloaded), plus optional CIFAR-10-C/TinyImageNet for richer shifts.\nliterature_review.md:197:  - Clean accuracy, robust accuracy (PGD/AutoAttack), AUROC/AUPR/FPR95, ECE/NLL.\nliterature_review.md:201:  - Evaluate both random perturbations and constrained directions (orthogonal/adversarial directions).\nresources.md:7:Total papers downloaded: 14 PDF files (12 core unique papers + 2 duplicate-named copies from initial retrieval pass).\nresources.md:31:| CIFAR-10 | 